"Groat" is an old Scottish word that refers to cereal made from hulledÂ oats.

Though it does take a little longer to prepare than cut or rolled oats, the exceptional hearty flavour and chewy nature of the resulting porridge definitely make it well worth the effort.
<h3>Source of our Oats</h3>
Oats, as we know them today, originate from the wild red oat, a plant which has origins in Asia. Oats were originally cultivated for medicinal purposes but have now become a food staple due to their numerous health benefits.

We import whole grain Oats from Western Australia which is one of the highest quality producers of this healthy grain. These Oats are thenÂ washed, hulled and dried in India and further processed at our facilities.
<h3>About ourÂ Oat Groats</h3>
OurÂ selectionÂ process helps ensure that only the best quality oats are selected to progress to the cleaning and cutting process. This minimal processing retains all of the nutrients that people look for in their oats.

Oats are a rich source of fibre, protein and magnesium. Not only are you able to eat them as oatmeal but they add health benefits to breads, bakesÂ and protein shakes. All of that simply makes our oats a cut above the rest.
<h3>Ingredients</h3>
Gluten free Whole grain Oats
<h3>Why Buy Our Oat Groats</h3>
At last, Oats that people with celiac disease or gluten intolerance can enjoy, too!

Oats are not only an excellent source of dietary fibre but they also reduce serum cholesterol levels in the body.

In comparison with most other whole grains, Oats are much higher in protein and healthy fats. They are also comparativelyÂ lower in carbohydrates. They contain more soluble fibre than other grains.

Oats contain more than 20 unique polyphenols, which have strong anti-oxidant, anti-inflammatory and anti-itching properties. They also have the best amino acid balance of all cereal grains.

Most of the Oats available commercially are Instant Oats, here is an article that compares the health benefitsÂ ofÂ <a href="http://www.cancerdietitian.com/2008/11/quick-oats-steel-cut-oats-or-regular-oats-whats-the-difference.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Quick Oats, Steel Cut Oats, or Regular Oats</a>

&nbsp;
<h3>How to use ourÂ Hulled Oats</h3>
<ul>
 	<li>Soak and consume as porridge</li>
 	<li>Bake into Breads, cereal</li>
</ul>
