Oat bran is the protective layer around oat groats that is loaded with fibre and other essential nutrients.

We love all types of oats. Be it the grainy oat groats or chewy steel cut oats. But the go to choice, for us is oat bran. It is easily cooked and gets a creamy, mushy texture that is reminiscent of the warmth of momâ€™s food.
<h3><strong>Source</strong></h3>
Oats was widely cultivated for its medicinal purposes and is now highly popular for its numerous health benefits. We import whole grain oats from West Australia which is known for its fine quality grains. Then the oats are further processed at our facilities in India.
<h3><strong>About our oat bran</strong></h3>
Our oat bran is lab tested gluten free, so people with gluten sensitivities (irritable bowel syndrome, celiac disease) can easily partake of it.Â Our oat bran is high in soluble dietary fibre. This gives the digestive system a boost. It is known to be helpful in weight loss and lowering cholesterol. Because it is a low GI food, it is recommended for consumption by diabetics.

A single cup of our oat bran provides:
<ul>
 	<li>50% of the fibre,</li>
 	<li>28% of the protein,</li>
 	<li>25% of the iron and</li>
 	<li>30% of thiamine that an adult requires everyday.</li>
</ul>
Additionally, it dishes out essential amounts of calcium, zinc, copper, manganese, selenium, riboflavin and amino acids.
<h3><strong>Why use our Oat Bran</strong></h3>
We work hard to make sure that 100% natural and only the finest quality oat groats are selected to move to the cleaning and cutting process. Minimal processing ensures that the oat bran retains its nutrients.

The creamy and soothing texture and nutty, naturally sweet flavour fosters your tummy and your taste buds!

Oat bran has a low glycemic index, which helps control blood glucose levels, making it a good choice for diabetics. Our oat bran is more natural and less processed. So it is a powerhouse of proteins, minerals, vitamins and the good fat.
<h3><strong>How to use</strong></h3>
Apart from being eaten as porridge, cooked with water or milk, when sprinkled on yogurt or blended in smoothies, it adds to their nutritional benefits. It can even be used in cakes and baked goods, to shallow fry or bake fish or make chickpea cutlets.

